# Atlas Workflows
Use the `atlas` CLI to inspect Datadog Atlas workflow executions.

## When to use
Use this skill when the user provides or asks about:
- `https://atlas.ddbuild.io/namespaces/<namespace>/workflows/<workflow-id>/<run-id>/history`
- `https://temporal.ddbuild.io/namespaces/<namespace>/workflows/<workflow-id>/<run-id>`
- Atlas workflow status, failure reason, input, history, child workflows, or activity failures.

## URL parsing
Parse URLs with this path shape:

```text
/namespaces/<namespace>/workflows/<workflow-id>/<run-id>[/history]
```

Extract:
- `namespace`
- `workflow-id`
- `run-id`
- host, to infer environment when possible

Example:

```text
https://atlas.ddbuild.io/namespaces/default/workflows/019df427-c144-7892-93c1-dfa809fe5c4b_44/019df427-d3a3-7401-b231-09da96462c45/history
```

Parsed:

```text
namespace=default
workflow-id=019df427-c144-7892-93c1-dfa809fe5c4b_44
run-id=019df427-d3a3-7401-b231-09da96462c45
```

## Find the Atlas target
If the user gives an explicit context/domain, use it.

For `atlas.ddbuild.io` or `temporal.ddbuild.io`, start with classic contexts. `prod` often backs ddbuild workflow URLs even when the workflow operates on staging clusters.

```fish
atlas context list
```

Try contexts in this order unless evidence suggests otherwise:

```text
prod
staging
dev
```

A quick existence probe:

```fish
atlas workflow input \
  -c <context> \
  -w '<workflow-id>' \
  -r '<run-id>' \
  --non-interactive
```

If the workflow is domain-based, use the domain form instead:

```fish
atlas workflow input \
  --domain <domain> \
  --datacenter <datacenter> \
  --partition <partition> \
  -w '<workflow-id>' \
  -r '<run-id>' \
  --non-interactive
```

Common domain datacenters include `us1.ddbuild.io`, `us1.staging.dog`, `us1.prod.dog`, `eu1.prod.dog`, and `eu1.staging.dog`. Ask when domain or datacenter cannot be inferred.

## Inspect status and failure tree
Prefer table output for status/failure analysis. It gives a compact tree of workflows, child workflows, activities, failures, task queue, and UI links.

Classic context:

```fish
atlas workflow watch \
  -c <context> \
  -w '<workflow-id>' \
  -r '<run-id>' \
  --all \
  --non-interactive
```

Domain-based:

```fish
atlas workflow watch \
  --domain <domain> \
  --datacenter <datacenter> \
  --partition <partition> \
  -w '<workflow-id>' \
  -r '<run-id>' \
  --all \
  --non-interactive
```

Use `--depth <n>` to limit large trees:

```fish
atlas workflow watch -c <context> -w '<workflow-id>' -r '<run-id>' --depth 2 --all --non-interactive
```

Avoid `--output jsonl` for first-pass failure analysis unless a structured stream is required; it can be noisy/repetitive for large workflows.

## Fetch input and output
Input:

```fish
atlas workflow input -c <context> -w '<workflow-id>' -r '<run-id>' --non-interactive | jq
```

Output, if completed:

```fish
atlas workflow output -c <context> -w '<workflow-id>' -r '<run-id>' --non-interactive | jq
```

## Fetch raw Temporal history
Use raw history for replay tests, event-level debugging, or payload extraction. It can be large; save to a file or summarize with `jq`.

Classic context:

```fish
atlas --context <context> -- \
  temporal workflow show \
    --workflow-id '<workflow-id>' \
    --run-id '<run-id>' \
    --namespace '<namespace>' \
    --output json > workflow_history.json
```

Domain-based:

```fish
atlas --domain <domain> --datacenter <datacenter> --partition <partition> -- \
  temporal workflow show \
    --workflow-id '<workflow-id>' \
    --run-id '<run-id>' \
    --namespace '<namespace>' \
    --output json > workflow_history.json
```

Summarize events:

```fish
jq -r '.history.events[] | [.eventId, .eventType] | @tsv' workflow_history.json | head -100
```

## Fetch event payload
Find an event ID from `atlas workflow watch` or raw history, then:

```fish
atlas workflow payload \
  -c <context> \
  -w '<workflow-id>' \
  -r '<run-id>' \
  --event-id <event-id> \
  --non-interactive | jq
```

## Answer format
When answering workflow status questions, include:
- status: completed, running, failed, canceled, timed out, or not found
- context/domain used
- workflow type, workflow ID, run ID, task queue
- input, if relevant and safe
- concise failure chain from top-level workflow to the root failing child/activity
- retry state and whether the failure is retryable, when visible
- next useful command or investigation target

For failures, lead with the cause. Example pattern:

```text
Status: failed.
Why: <top-level workflow> failed while <phase/action>. The failure chain is <child workflow/activity> -> <root error>. The root visible error is <message>; retry state is <state>.
```

## Safety and scope
- Read-only by default. Do not cancel, terminate, signal, or start workflows unless explicitly asked.
- Do not paste huge raw histories into chat. Summarize or write them to a temp file.
- If auth prompts appear, tell the user to complete Atlas/ddtool auth and retry.
- If multiple contexts match or environment is ambiguous, ask before drawing conclusions.
